Dialogue: 2,0:00:02.85,0:00:07.34,辉英,,0,0,0,,Get a free audio book plus a 30-day free trial by visiting the link below.
Dialogue: 1,0:00:07.86,0:00:11.30,辉中,,0,0,0,,1919年 飞行员Alcock和Brown
Dialogue: 2,0:00:07.86,0:00:11.30,辉英,,0,0,0,,In the year 1919, pilots Alcock and Brown
Dialogue: 1,0:00:11.30,0:00:15.94,辉中,,0,0,0,,驾驶飞机从加拿大飞往爱尔兰 完成了人类首次跨大西洋飞行
Dialogue: 2,0:00:11.30,0:00:15.94,辉英,,0,0,0,,completed the first non-stop transatlantic flight from Canada to Ireland.
Dialogue: 1,0:00:16.13,0:00:21.18,辉中,,0,0,0,,这趟旅程只花了他们16小时 但远没有想象的一帆风顺
Dialogue: 2,0:00:16.13,0:00:21.18,辉英,,0,0,0,,The journey took them just 16 hours, but it was anything but plain sailing.
Dialogue: 1,0:00:21.50,0:00:25.64,辉中,,0,0,0,,起飞时 超载的飞机几乎擦着一排树梢飞过
Dialogue: 2,0:00:21.50,0:00:25.64,辉英,,0,0,0,,During takeoff, the overloaded aircraft barely made it over a line of trees.
Dialogue: 1,0:00:25.76,0:00:32.10,辉中,,0,0,0,,过了不久 机载发电机坏了 导致他们没法用通信和加热设备
Dialogue: 2,0:00:25.76,0:00:32.10,辉英,,0,0,0,,And shortly after, the onboard generator failed, causing them to lose radio contact and their heating system.
Dialogue: 1,0:00:32.41,0:00:37.46,辉中,,0,0,0,,更惨的是 飞行员之后还遇到了突发的浓雾
Dialogue: 2,0:00:32.41,0:00:37.46,辉英,,0,0,0,,The pilots faced even more trouble when they were suddenly surrounded by a thick layer of fog.
Dialogue: 1,0:00:37.73,0:00:41.29,辉中,,0,0,0,,他们当时利用六分仪观星导航 浓雾让他们彻底迷失了方向
Dialogue: 2,0:00:37.73,0:00:41.29,辉英,,0,0,0,,Since they were using the stars to navigate, they became completely lost.
Dialogue: 1,0:00:41.40,0:00:47.00,辉中,,0,0,0,,低能见度又让Alcock发生空间迷向 螺旋俯冲后差点摔海里
Dialogue: 2,0:00:41.40,0:00:47.00,辉英,,0,0,0,,And the lack of visibility caused Alcock to lose control of the aircraft, narrowly missing the sea.
Dialogue: 1,0:00:47.62,0:00:53.26,辉中,,0,0,0,,在经历了暴风雪和在爱尔兰轻微的摔机着陆后 飞行员们终于成功横跨了大西洋
Dialogue: 2,0:00:47.62,0:00:53.26,辉英,,0,0,0,,One snow storm later and a minor crash landing in Ireland, the pilots made it across the Atlantic.
Dialogue: 1,0:00:53.65,0:00:58.30,辉中,,0,0,0,,这次伟大成就最终成为了人类航空旅行的开端
Dialogue: 2,0:00:53.65,0:00:58.30,辉英,,0,0,0,,This major accomplishment ultimately led to the beginning of passenger air travel.
Dialogue: 1,0:00:58.77,0:01:04.73,辉中,,0,0,0,,但Alcock和Brown的极其艰难的旅程恰恰体现了飞行员职责的重要性
Dialogue: 2,0:00:58.77,0:01:04.73,辉英,,0,0,0,,But Alcock and Brown's incredibly rough journey showed just how essential the role of the pilot was.
Dialogue: 1,0:01:05.37,0:01:08.66,辉中,,0,0,0,,40年后 在人类航天的起步阶段
Dialogue: 2,0:01:05.37,0:01:08.66,辉英,,0,0,0,,40 years later and with spaceflight just around the corner,
Dialogue: 1,0:01:08.66,0:01:15.21,辉中,,0,0,0,,NASA启动了X-15计划 来探究人类与航天器如何应对太空飞行
Dialogue: 2,0:01:08.66,0:01:15.21,辉英,,0,0,0,,NASA set up the X-15 program to determine how humans and aircraft would cope with flights into space.
Dialogue: 1,0:01:15.62,0:01:18.18,辉中,,0,0,0,,X-15是一款以火箭为动力的飞机
Dialogue: 2,0:01:15.62,0:01:18.18,辉英,,0,0,0,,The X-15 was a rocket-powered aircraft,
Dialogue: 1,0:01:18.18,0:01:24.20,辉中,,0,0,0,,飞行高度可达100km 速度可达7000km/h
Dialogue: 2,0:01:18.18,0:01:24.20,辉英,,0,0,0,,capable of reaching altitudes above 100km and speeds of 7,000km/h
Dialogue: 1,0:01:24.68,0:01:29.40,辉中,,0,0,0,,该计划的主要目标是探究人类在太空飞行中的极限
Dialogue: 2,0:01:24.68,0:01:29.40,辉英,,0,0,0,,One of the main goals of the program was to explore the limitations of humans in spaceflight
Dialogue: 1,0:01:29.40,0:01:33.00,辉中,,0,0,0,,——找出哪些是人类擅长的 哪些是计算机擅长的
Dialogue: 2,0:01:29.40,0:01:33.00,辉英,,0,0,0,,—find out what humans are better at and what computers are better at.
Dialogue: 1,0:01:33.65,0:01:39.89,辉中,,0,0,0,,经历了9年 199次飞行后 NASA发现 人类虽然能驾驶火箭进入太空
Dialogue: 2,0:01:33.65,0:01:39.89,辉英,,0,0,0,,After 9 years and 199 flights, NASA found that while a human could fly a rocket into space,
Dialogue: 1,0:01:40.10,0:01:44.12,辉中,,0,0,0,,但自动系统却能完成相同的任务且精度更高
Dialogue: 2,0:01:40.10,0:01:44.12,辉英,,0,0,0,,the automated system could perform the same task with much more accuracy.
Dialogue: 1,0:01:44.72,0:01:47.04,辉中,,0,0,0,,随着NASA把重心放在了火箭上
Dialogue: 2,0:01:44.72,0:01:47.04,辉英,,0,0,0,,Once NASA switched their attention to rockets,
Dialogue: 1,0:01:47.04,0:01:52.30,辉中,,0,0,0,,人类在火箭上的职责也开始明确——不是驾驶火箭 而是监督火箭
Dialogue: 2,0:01:47.04,0:01:52.30,辉英,,0,0,0,,it was clear that the role of the human would not be to fly the rocket, but to monitor what it was doing.
Dialogue: 1,0:01:52.72,0:01:55.80,辉中,,0,0,0,,虽然飞机可以仅由两名飞行员驾驶
Dialogue: 2,0:01:52.72,0:01:55.80,辉英,,0,0,0,,While an airplane can be flown with just a couple of pilots,
Dialogue: 1,0:01:55.80,0:02:01.97,辉中,,0,0,0,,但火箭却需要一个完整的团队在任务控制中心持续监看火箭的每一部分
Dialogue: 2,0:01:55.80,0:02:01.97,辉英,,0,0,0,,a rocket takes a whole team of people back at mission control, to constantly monitor each part of the rocket.
Dialogue: 1,0:02:02.72,0:02:05.56,辉中,,0,0,0,,到了今天 火箭的发射已经完全自动化
Dialogue: 2,0:02:02.72,0:02:05.56,辉英,,0,0,0,,To this day, rocket launches are completely automated.
Dialogue: 1,0:02:05.77,0:02:07.76,辉中,,0,0,0,,以重型猎鹰火箭为例
Dialogue: 2,0:02:05.77,0:02:07.76,辉英,,0,0,0,,Take the Falcon Heavy for example.
Dialogue: 1,0:02:08.02,0:02:13.34,辉中,,0,0,0,,发射前60秒 火箭箭载计算机接管飞行控制
Dialogue: 2,0:02:08.02,0:02:13.34,辉英,,0,0,0,,60 seconds before launch, the rockets onboard computers take control of the flight.
Dialogue: 1,0:02:13.53,0:02:17.36,辉中,,0,0,0,,从这一刻开始 火箭的这些操作 全靠它自己！
Dialogue: 2,0:02:13.53,0:02:17.36,辉英,,0,0,0,,And from then on, the rocket does this, all by itself!
Dialogue: 1,0:02:17.80,0:02:22.14,辉中,,0,0,0,,如果火箭都能做到 那为什么民航飞机不能没有飞行员呢？
Dialogue: 2,0:02:17.80,0:02:22.14,辉英,,0,0,0,,If a rocket can do this, then why can't an airliner fly without a pilot?
Dialogue: 1,0:02:22.94,0:02:26.69,辉中,,0,0,0,,虽然现代民航飞机有很完善的自动驾驶系统
Dialogue: 2,0:02:22.94,0:02:26.69,辉英,,0,0,0,,Although modern airliners have very capable autopilot systems,
Dialogue: 1,0:02:26.69,0:02:31.74,辉中,,0,0,0,,但主要功能是减少飞行员的工作量 而不是驾驶飞机
Dialogue: 2,0:02:26.69,0:02:31.74,辉英,,0,0,0,,their main job is to reduce the workload for the pilot and not to fly the plane.
Dialogue: 1,0:02:32.18,0:02:36.29,辉中,,0,0,0,,而这也不代表飞机全自动飞行是不可能的
Dialogue: 2,0:02:32.18,0:02:36.29,辉英,,0,0,0,,However, this doesn't mean it's impossible for an aircraft to fly itself.
Dialogue: 1,0:02:36.80,0:02:41.24,辉中,,0,0,0,,回到1947年 美国空军进行了一次飞行试验
Dialogue: 2,0:02:36.80,0:02:41.24,辉英,,0,0,0,,Back in 1947, the US Air Force performed an experimental flight
Dialogue: 1,0:02:41.24,0:02:45.05,辉中,,0,0,0,,使用C-54"空中霸王"飞机从加拿大飞往英国
Dialogue: 2,0:02:41.24,0:02:45.05,辉英,,0,0,0,,from Canada to England using a C-54 Skymaster.
Dialogue: 1,0:02:45.42,0:02:49.52,辉中,,0,0,0,,飞行员将载有7名成员的飞机滑行到跑道上
Dialogue: 2,0:02:45.42,0:02:49.52,辉英,,0,0,0,,With a seven-man crew onboard, the pilot taxied onto the runway,
Dialogue: 1,0:02:49.52,0:02:53.48,辉中,,0,0,0,,按下了自动驾驶接通按钮 将控制权交给了飞机
Dialogue: 2,0:02:49.52,0:02:53.48,辉英,,0,0,0,,let go of the controls and pushed a button to engage the autopilot.
Dialogue: 1,0:02:53.96,0:02:55.92,辉中,,0,0,0,,飞机自己完成了起飞
Dialogue: 2,0:02:53.96,0:02:55.92,辉英,,0,0,0,,The plane took off by itself,
Dialogue: 1,0:02:55.92,0:03:01.64,辉中,,0,0,0,,自动调整了襟翼和油门 离地后自动收回了起落架
Dialogue: 2,0:02:55.92,0:03:01.64,辉英,,0,0,0,,automatically adjusting its flaps and throttles and, once airborne, retracting its landing gear.
Dialogue: 1,0:03:01.96,0:03:04.41,辉中,,0,0,0,,随后按照事先编写好的程序 飞机自己按照一系列流程横跨了大西洋
Dialogue: 2,0:03:01.96,0:03:04.41,辉英,,0,0,0,,It then flew itself across the Atlantic,
Dialogue: 1,0:03:04.41,0:03:10.72,辉中,,0,0,0,,随后按照事先编写好的程序 飞机自己按照一系列流程横跨了大西洋
Dialogue: 2,0:03:04.41,0:03:10.72,辉英,,0,0,0,,following a series of sequences that had been programmed into its "mechanical brain".
Dialogue: 1,0:03:11.02,0:03:18.17,辉中,,0,0,0,,在第二天黎明时分 C-53抵达了英国的海岸 并进行了一次完美的着陆
Dialogue: 2,0:03:11.02,0:03:18.17,辉英,,0,0,0,,At dawn the following day, the C-54 reach the English coast and executed a perfect landing.
Dialogue: 1,0:03:18.54,0:03:22.88,辉中,,0,0,0,,以上节选自Nicholas Carr的有声书"The Glass Cage"
Dialogue: 2,0:03:18.54,0:03:22.88,辉英,,0,0,0,,This was a sample from an audiobook called "The Glass Cage" by Nicholas Carr.
Dialogue: 1,0:03:22.98,0:03:25.65,辉中,,0,0,0,,这是一本展望自动化未来的有声书
Dialogue: 2,0:03:22.98,0:03:25.65,辉英,,0,0,0,,It's an audiobook that looks at the future of automation.
Dialogue: 1,0:03:25.73,0:03:30.08,辉中,,0,0,0,,探索了机器人、自动驾驶汽车、数字化医疗等领域
Dialogue: 2,0:03:25.73,0:03:30.08,辉英,,0,0,0,,Exploring things like robots, self-driving cars, and digitized medicine.
Dialogue: 1,0:03:30.44,0:03:34.70,辉中,,0,0,0,,这本书和很多其他书都在Audible上有有声书的版本
Dialogue: 2,0:03:30.44,0:03:34.70,辉英,,0,0,0,,This book along with many others, is available as an audiobook on Audible,
